Someone’s National Insurance record could have a significant bearing on how much state pension they can get. It is therefore important for Britons to maintain a strong record. To get the full new state pension, Britons could need up to 35 qualifying years on their record. For the full basic state pension, it is 30 years. These years do not have to be consecutive. To get any state pension at all, an individual could need at least 10 qualifying years on their record. READ MORE: State pensioners could miss out on full pension by giving wrong child benefit details Some people may still get less than the full sum, regardless of their National Insurance record, if they were contracted out before April 6, 2016. Britons can check their record online through the Gov.uk website to see if there are any gaps in their record. It is possible for someone to have gaps in their record and still get the full state pension, as long as they have the required number of years overall. If someone finds they are not on course to receive the full state pension, they may be able to improve their National Insurance record before reaching state pension age. DON'T MISSPIP claim: 87 muscle and joint conditions that could mean you get £627 a month from DWP [INSIGHT]Lloyds Bank issues new scam warning - 'If it's seems fishy - you're probably right' [WARNING]PIP claim: The full list of freebies and discounts available from DWP - worth thousands [BENEFITS] Qualifying years for National Insurance can be earned in three different ways: Those who are working pay National Insurance and get a qualifying year if: Some benefits come with attached National Insurance credits which could allow Britons to earn qualifying years. This includes: If someone still wishes to increase their state pension entitlement after exhausting other options, they may be able to pay voluntary contributions to earn more qualifying years.